"Initially, 'Artificial Intelligence' aimed to develop machines capable of performing tasks that required human-like reasoning. Yet, the term has been co-opted by commercial interests, leading to widespread misconceptions about the capabilities of current technologies. What is often marketed as AI does not truly exhibit independent thinking or understanding but operates through sophisticated algorithms that analyze patterns from vast datasets, including user interactions and social media dialogues. These systems, known as large language models (LLMs), automate responses based on predetermined rules and data patterns, not genuine cognition. The misrepresentation of these capabilities has diluted the term 'AI', prompting the introduction of 'AGI' (Artificial General Intelligence). This new term was created to reclaim the original vision of AI, indicating a future technology that can authentically replicate human cognitive abilities, distinct from the limited functionalities of today's LLMs."

There are so many things wrong about this, its crazy:

First of all, a transformer is simply an architecture of a neural network. In the beginning he states that transformers are new AI models that learn more if you give it more data; that is literally the case with EVERY AI. That also comes with many advantages AND disadvantages.

The other thing he said was that one of the neurons in the transformer model OpenAI was testing was able to be the world's best at sentiment analysis; this is simply not true and that is not how AI works. All these neurons simply hold values and work together to solve an object. So, for example, if you were asked to tell whether a message is happy or sad (0 or 1), the model's neuron at the end either says 0 or 1 based on the activation function. So, to  summarize, a single neuron can't be crazy good at sentiment analysis. 

Also he says that AI is something we don't completely understand yet: not true AT ALL. Honestly, it's really all math. If you wanted, you could literally take a notebook and do the exact same process an AI follows. We literally made AIs and we know exactly what happens. It's written out to be this "Black Box" which is simply not true. The only instance when this is true is during its training process, which doesn't really matter much anyways.

Actually, nearly everything YOU have said is untrue. It is not the case that simply adding  more and more training data increases quality of all AI models. The great thing about Alpha Go is not that it coud be fed more and more Go games and it would get better, the great thing about Alpha go is that it used reinforcement learning to increase its ability on to achieve the win conditions of the game Go far beyond the human data it was fed. Now, you could describe how Alpha Go worked as pumping it with more "winning" Go strategy data, but it isn't the Data which is key, it is the reinforced behavior down steam of its ability to attempt to meet the win condition of the game,
It is true that there is not one "neuron" that was the best at sentiment analysis, this description was misleading and was likely a translation of a simplified explanation of the unique phenomenon which remains significant, which is that the top sentiment analysis in the world was accidentally achieved downstream of the generalized data the model was trained on. So whether "one neuron" did this is irrelevant, because the point remains.
For you next point, you are completely wrong, except in the most pedantic sense. Yes, we understand how neural networks work, in the general, but the size of these transformer model neural networks is such that any particular ability or answer is the result of a system we do not understand in total. So we can't point to "ah yes, neural layer 27 is why it does this." Or, anything of the sort. So, the point, and all the downstream implications of this point, are true and well taken.
I also don't want people to be afraid of AI but a useful and safe AI future is not achieved by shutting down conversations about the weaknesses or strengths of the technology.

Howdy hi hi,
     AI, is still just a jack in the box.  Just like it's not the nukes themselves you should fear, rather it's the international community and the leaders of nations who have the power to use them.  This like that, is more a matter of being aware of how clever people do, and will use these tools to disrupt various aspects of life.  To say that anyone should be afraid of AI, is like saying that we should fear computers because of what was presented in the movie 2001: A space odyssey.  One thing does not follow the other.  
     So here we have a computer program designed to predict what a human being might say next.  You see some level of success in this, then guys like this start running around with their hair on fire screaming that the sky is falling like chicken little.  This fear is, just like the only universal fear, based on a lack of knowledge.  We don't understand as of yet, what makes us intelligent.  And based on that fear, people sow together all these stories about how some day the computers will just spontaneously become self aware.
     The example I like to use:  Imagine you build the world's largest library.  Everything ever written by every person ever is printed in book form and stored in this building.  Even if you gave every book the ability to reference every other book.  This is never going to just magically get smart.  Most people know this is true intuitively.  The reason for this is that there is no mechanism available in this scenario for the building and all its data to evolve.  AI is no different, it is a singular process designed to be predictive of what a person would say.  And what that comes down to is just this.  The AI has formed a table of contents, and in that data stored how frequently each reference  is accessed.  Then following a few simple rules, spits out an answer.  This is not intellect, this is a parrot repeating the sounds it hears all the time.  And it is the fear of the unknown, that lend this kind of commenter, an appearance of authenticity.
     The other thing that is missing, not just a mechanism for rewriting its own code.  But it has no survival dynamic, and it has nothing that is putting pressure on it to evolve.  A tea cup isn't going to evolve into a thermos bottle on its own.  A person, however, might crush that tea cup and use the powder they obtain from the cup as part of the insulation in the thermos.  Sure that could happen.  But a teacup in the wilds of your cupboards.  Yeah, that's just not going to happen.  As such I stand by my assertion that it is far more concerning, the things people will do with these new tools.

So I just went and asked it about it's limitations and got this:

Lack of common sense and contextual understanding: AI models may struggle to understand context or make sense of information in the same way humans do, leading to errors or misunderstandings in certain situations.

Data dependency: AI models heavily rely on data for training and decision-making. If the training data is biased, incomplete, or unrepresentative, the AI may produce biased or inaccurate results.

Narrow expertise: Most AI systems are specialized in specific tasks and lack the broad, flexible intelligence of humans. They may perform exceptionally well within their specific domain but struggle with tasks outside their scope.

Interpretability: Some AI models, particularly deep learning models, can be difficult to interpret, making it challenging to understand why they make specific decisions or predictions.

Ethical and societal implications: AI raises ethical concerns related to privacy, bias, job displacement, and societal impact. Addressing these concerns requires careful consideration and oversight.

Robustness and adversarial attacks: AI systems can be vulnerable to adversarial attacks, where maliciously crafted inputs cause them to produce incorrect outputs. Ensuring the robustness and security of AI systems remains a challenge.

Resource requirements: Training and running AI models can require significant computational resources, limiting their accessibility to organizations with sufficient computing power and expertise.

Continual learning: Many AI models lack the ability to learn incrementally over time from new data or experiences in the way humans do. Developing AI systems capable of continual learning remains an ongoing area of research.

Being a user of AI, I find it an amazing revolutionary technology. AI is a bulldozer for unstructured digital information (documents, audio, video, social media posts, etc). There was a time when ditches were dug by hand using men with shovels and animals. Then along came the game changing backhoe. Likewise a person using AI can craft written works, images, and videos in short order that would take an enormous amount of time or require a big team to accomplish. 

AI is an aggregator of the information it was trained on. It does not create anything new. It effectively disassembles it's training data and then reassembles it in a new way under the direction of a human.  It is an extremely clever mechanism but is always using those "Lego bricks" found in the training data. Lego bricks have their limitations. When you sign up for ChatGPT, for example, you are warned that the AI can give out wrong answers. Not that it tells lies, but if the training data was wrong then the results will be wrong. As with all computer systems garbage in => garbage out.  

While I do think AI is a completely amazing set of tools that will propel humanity into a new era, I do not believe that it will ever be sentient. Furthermore it seems to me that the AI industry pushes this idea (the singularity) as well as the idea that AI is smarter than humans. This looks like juiced up marketing. The software industry is famous for selling "vapor-ware". That is products that don't exist but can reasonably be expected to be delivered in a given amount of time with given resources. Many times in the past these products were complete failures as the underlying assumptions of what could be done by when turned out to be wrong. These stories about sentient AI are always peppered with words like "could" or "may" and are IMHO just hype to fill up the sales queue.

AI is not going to take your job. But somebody using an AI will. Likewise AI will not take over the world but somebody using AI could - if humanity believes in this sentient AI super intelligence mythology and submits. Recall the Wizard of Oz. When the curtain was pulled on the fire breathing dragon there was a human at the controls.

5:00 -- No; Joe Rogan does not understand the implications of what he just said. Throwing all this data over increasing amounts of compute power is the path to a lot of neato things computers can become capable of; however, this is not the path to "AGI" & it never will be -- Ned Block of NYU demolished this notion some time ago. Creating AI in this manner is 1. radically infeasible, but 2. never a dynamic enough machine for the sort of emergence AGI necessitates. This is where these fellas believe AGI will emerge & it's unfortunate that two individuals presenting on the state of the art of AI don't really see this because people see all this new neato stuff & they generally become easily convinced of a looming threat that is never really there -- just because GPT-4 can do a lot of things doesn't give anyone the inferential right to say GPT-n will be able to do anything better than GPT-4, let alone things exponentially better than GPT-4. 

Indeed, the brick wall is soon approaching -- either someone is going to have to come out & admit AI is much further out than our current technological capability OR there needs to be a substantial revolution in other models of computation to maintain forward momentum. Why the latter is important doesn't even register for most of these individuals in AI. Even after that is understood, there's another substantial hurdle one must overcome before AI ...or AGI arises. & That will require an amount of humility that is not normally found in humans subject to a free market economy. But let's say that individual is found & is ready to make it happen -- before he or she flips the switch, their penultimate task will then be alignment. Arguably, this will be one of the simplest tasks to achieve in this 70+ year pursuit (thus far) for legitimate Artificial Intelligence (AGI) to finally emerge. 

Given what lies ahead though, we are nowhere close to developing AGI. In fact, so much stands in the way, it will never happen because human beings are motivated by remarkably simple things -- once we've developed a non-AI machine (we'll call it "AI") that can sufficiently satisfy most/all of those needs, it will be given the rubber stamp of "AGI" & the actual pursuit of AGI stops then & there. Why build AI when non-AI can do everything you want & can do it exceedingly well? Where's the motivation for AGI? It's done. In other words, once the sex bots arrive, aka the really good "AGI", you can pretty much forget about AGI & all its supposed threats...(?) & To be clear, we are way closer to the sex bots thing than we are AGI.

I worked with Natural Language Processing (NLP) when Transformer models were coming out back in College. My first work project was using Natural Language processing to parse legal documents for a company that services law firms using BERT. I learned about sentiment analysis and how NLP models are able to ‚Äúunderstand‚Äù human emotions from text. I can 100% with certainty tell you that this guy is talking out of his behind and Machine learning models are trained to do that. Sentiment analysis has been a study of machine learning that dates way back, I think the 80‚Äôs, it‚Äôs not something that came out of transformer models. What makes Transformer models so special is that they are able to remember previous context so they are able to analyze larger bodies of text. Sentiment analysis is part of text parsing and is purposely added into the mix so the Machine learning model is able to understand the context of text better. (When I say understand text better, I don‚Äôt mean understand like us humans understand, all NLP models essentially break down text into pieces, and text has to go through different steps that process text and pass it on to the next step in the neural network. There is one step incharge of understanding the sentiment of corpus (text) this ‚Äúone neuron‚Äù that does best in the world at understanding human sentiment, does so well because it‚Äôs incharge of doing that.scientists didn‚Äôt just come across this by mistake, they added this on purpose. FFS)  Also  the reason why transformer models do so much better the more data you feed it, it‚Äôs because the whole purpose of the transformer is to keep what it already analyzed in memory, so the more data you give it, the more it has in memory so it‚Äôs able to put the context of two different bodies of text together. It‚Äôs not out of magic, this was purposely done. This also isn‚Äôt something new, NLP has been implemented and studied since the 60‚Äôs (I think earlier) the hardware was just not there yet to be realized as well as it is now, but these concepts including sentiment analysis helping machines understand text has already been studied. There are limitations to transformer models, you can‚Äôt just keep feeding it data, because it will begin to slow down since it can‚Äôt process so much and what they have found (atleast back when bert was new) was that NLP models begin to hallucinate (make connections that are not correct) you need to increase the size of the neural network and it helps but after some point it doesn‚Äôt either.

1:54 interesting point that nobody bring up

AI is too much of a blanket term.  So much of AI is so powerful and so useful and not dangerous... like 95% of it.  It can be used in games HEAVILY.

The gaming industry can really use AI.  Especially in immersive RPG type games.  You want random NPC that you can just chat with in the world to make say a village more realistic?  You want to be able to have the player talk to the NPC with his real voice?  Heck these NPC could draw or lore, events that have happened in the area, time of day, jobs, weather... anything.  They could make up a personality and heck you could even romance them.  All this without impacting the actual story line as you can put restrictions easily on what information they have access to.  AI could handle things like the villagers going to work, working, taking breaks, going home, cooking and cleaning, going to bed... having families and friends...  Stuff that no game developer could afford to program into a game.

The other great thing and AI can di is changing voices.  This will greatly reduce the number of voice actors in animations and games.  They might even be able to do the acting themselves.  AI could also put detail into a scene that would be very tedious to do manually.  They could likely handle designs of props and such for these games and animations or even do some special effects in movies.  This would greatly reduce production costs.  Yes it might completely replace a large percentage of actors and programmers eventually.  It can also edit photographs.

AI can also run data and simulators with a wider range of variables and should be able to help develop things like better alloys, new medicines, better batteries...  It could help design stronger structures, time traffic lights, design intersections for better flow...  It could design and layout manufacturing systems that are faster and more efficient.  Really IA is going to be the key to solving a lot of things, like curing cancer, creating better treatments for killing bacteria and viruses and maybe even figuring out how to do cold fusion.

They can run though algorithms and such to do things like improve the safety of self driving cars or stabilize flight controls for pilots and such.  Even in the military they could greatly improve targeting systems and the ability to pick out potential targets using, radar, IR, or even visual cameras.  Giving AI too much control in these areas is where the danger comes from and this is where we need to be careful.  It is when you let AI, not just augment systems but control systems and let them mess together.  The more that can do things on their own the more dangerous.  Having them come up with the algorithms to make self driving cars safer is great, but having them control the cars and be able to improve they own algorithms is where things can go wrong.  We can not take people that far out of the picture.  AI is a tool and should be used as a tool.

*sigh* I have many problems with this attempt at an explanation, but I just want to be clear here: Transformer models like this do NOT understand subjects they generate content about.  They are predictive engines using probability and a giant amount of reference material, which is a fancy way of saying they generate what may plausibly come next.  Keyword there is "plausibly", I didn't say what "should" or "correctly" comes next.  

To take the example of chemistry, by reading enough chemistry textbooks it can predict what a textbook might say about a certain topic but it doesn't know if the textbook is correct about it.  If they're smart about the training they might bias the textbooks to be considered authoritative, but let's say you also give it a database of published research papers and claim they're authoritative too and expect that will make it smarter... only instead it now knows about research on potential truths, papers showing established theories might have issues, and worst of all it has incorrect papers that haven't been replicated or challenged.  The model isn't a chemist, it only knows what it has seen, it hasn't had a human fact check most of it.  That's before we even start with conflicting models we use at different levels, like what is the model predicting off if you ask it for a description of an atom?  We can hope it won't spit out Rutherford, but will it give one based on orbits, shells or quantum probabilistics?  Better yet, is it properly distinguishing stuff it learned from a textbook from stuff it learned on wikipedia or reddit?

Now apply that to every single field of knowledge.

Think that's bad enough?  It gets worse: things like chatgpt are designed to favour the human's opinion over the model's idea of truth.  You can convince a model that it is wrong about facts or that lies are true, assuming you got it to give you a correct answer in the first place.  It doesn't understand things, it lacks the ability to properly handle liars.
And none of this is particularly surprising if you know how the thing works, no more than that sentiment analysis is surprising, because those are things which are exactly what the model is designed to do.  Take text, analyse based on training material to produce a parameter set, predict what comes next based on what it has learned about text with a similar parameter set.
One or two neurons are doing something particularly interestingly?  There are billions of neurons in the model.  Statistics of big numbers will hold true.

This guy's biggest mistake- to my mind- is that he's sorta _begging the question._ He's assuming the conclusion.
He's ascribing to it human traits. He's fully anthropomorphised this A.I. when- based on my understanding of programming- there is absolutely no reason whatsoever to do.
It's a bit like saying "Water only ever wants to flow downwards and never wants to flow upwards." When you say something like that, you're ascribing an agency to this water. Not only that, you're also imbuing the water with human motivations for its behaviour. Before long, you've fully anthropomorphised the Water and you're explaining to people that this drought is caused by Old Man Water, who is a sociopath and who just wants to harm humans...

Anyway, that's the mistake that this guy has made. Any one of us could easily have made it, unfortunately, his mistake is public and showcases his lack of knowledge of programming/ of how computers work.

@@ReubenAStern 
You are correct in saying that instructions or rather understanding program flows matter. They do immensely especially when dealing with large amounts of data moving around quickly. Entropy applies even in a digital space if allowed. An easy example is say a global array piping in from several data sources. Simple but innocuous in how it might not work as intended. Obviously it's global so we can call it from wherever which is convenient but as a result may be called at the same time depending on your application. Second might be a matter of the buffer and how that's handled capped or filtered. My point being is that it really boils down to programming methodology and tuning down how you isolate data flows. If you're piping in data from multiple sources then there is a greater chance that any certain data type will either be misread or skewed. And then it has a downstream cascade effect as instances stack. So your system of filtering has to be robust and done pre process otherwise you're going to have instability. Similar reason why we can't just open end everything* and hope it becomes recursive. Quite simply we have absolute values for variable storage. Granted we can index and tokenize to expand that and program to grab average value and dump to cap safely on storage but eventually you reach a plateau of the collective amount of average that is allowed. In the early days of microcontrollers before Arduino esp32 and pis you had a basic stamp. Great learning tool because of it's ridiculous hardware limits you had kb to work within. So you had to often use hex and think individually about everything that was being programmed stored and processed.

What they say about the transformer model is just not correct. The unique thing about the transformer neural network architecture isn't that it gets better with more data and compute - that's true of all neural networks and has been known since 2012 when an architecture called the convolutional neural network (AlexNet) was used to win a large scale image recognition competition. AlexNet basically proved that with a lot of data, the right architecture, and a lot of compute a neural net can do amazing things. The unique thing about the transformer neural networks, like GPT, is something called "attention". Basically, as it's generating each word, its looking back on all the other words and computing an "attention score" that says how much should I pay attention to this word when I'm generating the next word. This allows it to focus on the relevant parts of the text. This attention process is itself learned by the transformer, not programmed directly by the programmer. Also, GPT does not stand for "General Purpose Transformer" like these guys say lmao. (Idk if it's in this clip, but its in the episode). GPT stands for "Generatively Pre-trained Transformer" Generative refers to the fact that it's learning by trying to generate the next word in the text it's "reading". Each time it generates a word, It's literally generating a "probability distribution" over all the words in it's dictionary - that means for every word it assigns a number between 0 and 1 for how likely that word is to come next - every single word, and the numbers for all the words have to add up to 1, thats what makes it a "probability distribution". And so you can "sample" from that distribution, not always having to choose the word the transformer thinks is most likely. You can add some randomness in how you select from that distribution, that's how ChatGPT can generate different responses to the same prompt. The "P" stands for "Pretrained" which just refers to the fact that this learning by reading the internet and predicting the next word is really meant to be a first step in a two step process. The "pre" training on the internet is just for it to learn all kinds of stuff and basically have common sense, then you can train it further on your specific use case, like internal documentation for your company.

Katharina Zweig, a professor at the University of Kaiserslautern/Germany, describes ChatGPT as ‚Äúautocorrection on steroids.‚Äù  This captures the principle behind the AI quite accurately: ChatGPT guesses which word is most likely to follow another because the algorithm has ‚Äúlearned‚Äù which words occur in which context.  The answer to the question ‚ÄúWho is Chancellor‚Äù is ‚ÄúRobert Habeck‚Äù, because the word ‚ÄúRobert Habeck‚Äù often appears in the context of ‚ÄúChancellor‚Äù.  This is also the reason for the so-called hallucinating when ChatGPT presents fictitious scientific literature or legal precedents with full conviction.

The thought experiment with the Chinese room comes from John Searle: A man who doesn't understand a word of Chinese is given a manual that contains extensive instructions about which Chinese characters (answers) are likely to follow which Chinese characters (questions).  When (for him incomprehensible) Chinese questions in the form of characters are passed to him through a crack in the room, he can produce the correct (or probable) answer.  He finds the correct (or probable) output using the manual, the algorithm.  It looks like the man understands Chinese.  In fact, he doesn't understand anything.  ChatGPT also doesn't know that it doesn't understand anything because it doesn't experience anything. 

Even if the man's manual in our parable is constantly fed with more petabytes of learning data (he then becomes better and better at simulating seemingly intelligent behavior), no ‚Äúemergence‚Äù occurs.  ChatGPT will never understand anything because experiencing and understanding are fundamentally different than algorithms, data or neural networks.  Even the neural network brain does not create consciousness, it is just the prerequisite for it.  Here a look at recent research in the area of embodiment and enactive mind is fruitful: Consciousness only arises through the living, physical being in the world, the need to find one's way in the world, and also includes the implicit, incorporated  and intuitive knowledge that results from dealing with the world, ‚Äúknowing how‚Äù.  Erwin Straus once summed it up: People think ‚Äì not the brain.  If one follows these newer approaches, it is ultimately the metabolism of living organisms that creates the prerequisites for consciousness and thus for qualia.

The evolution of AI is both inspiring and unsettling. What strikes the most is the unforeseen emergence of capabilities in AI systems, particularly during 2023. This phenomenon raises crucial questions about the boundaries of AI development and the ethical implications of such rapid advancement. While the video highlights impressive feats like sentiment analysis, research-grade chemistry, and theory of mind assessments, it also inadvertently underscores a profound dilemma: the unpredictability of AI's developmental trajectory has somewhat been very underscored in the media and by the global psyche. 

One key aspect not fully addressed is the societal impact of AI's emergent abilities. For example, if an AI can inadvertently learn to perform research-grade chemistry, including potentially hazardous applications like VX nerve gas synthesis, what does this mean for global security? If an AI can model and predict human behavior and thought processes at an advanced level, how will this impact privacy, autonomy, and even our understanding of human agency?

Their analysis about the need for 'aligned AGI' is crucial but raises another set of questions. How do we ensure alignment in a context where AI's capabilities are continuously and unpredictably expanding? Who defines the alignment parameters, and how do we account for the diversity of human values and ethics globally?

Overall I believe, the question is not just about what AI can or cannot do, but more importantly, about what it SHOULD do, and WHO gets to make these decisions.

People seem to think that ChatGPT 'thinks', it doesn't. It finds patterns across multiple things and is able to pool from those patterns and apply it to other things. Just like predictive text works on your phone's keyboard it's not reading your mind it's using data to better predict what would be the next word or character. The fact it can do this type of pattern recognition across a lot of stuff doesn't suddenly make it "conscious".

Ok - can we just get a few things straight:

Emergent behaviour is not a sign of sentience - GPTs are not alive, they don't "think" and they aren't going to SkyNet us, since they are simply a text processing model trained on a lot of data. The "behaviours" are really held in the training data and the clever way a GPT creates relationships between those data. 

Basically, GPT is just really good at taking input, running it through a complex model and producing output.

GPTs do not think. GPTs cannot grow independently of being trained. GPTs are not sentient.

Now, that doesn't mean someone can't take a GPT, train it on some data and ask it to do things with that data that give them knowledge they wouldn't be able to discern for themselves - but that's a different story. 

AI is just a tool, can we stop scaremongering Terminator scenarios and worry more about how people will use the tool?

FYI, you can download various GPT versions and train them on your own data set (or even write your own mini-GPT if you want) - does that mean your computer will grow arms and legs and beat you to death with an old 3.5" HDD? Probably not.

Okay guys so you got that completely wrong, that's not how it works at all. Transformers did not change anything to the you pump more data and it learns more stuff. You're misunderstanding the thing. Transformers are nice because they perform a full matrix multiplication which is faster than RNN and also means that each token gets to see each other at each layer reducing the depth of the network compared to RNN and allowing us to go deeper.

What you're talking about is a completely different thing, it is unsupervised learning, more specifically self supervised learning and generative pretraining.

Labelling has been part of machine learning for a long time, people remember the change that imagenet represented in vision. Having data which is correctly labeled has been used in the past for your downstream task like mnist where you train your model to recognize characters, but it also has been used on massive data with the idea that if you learn to categorize massive data you will be able to understand underlying structure of that data.

Basically, learn to distinguish before dogs and cats and the model will have a concept of what a dog and a cat is and you can use the last hidden layer of your thing.

But the issue with labelling data is that it is extremely time intensive and requires human work. So the amount of labelled data at one time is always way smaller than the amount of unlabelled data. So to be able to unlock all that unlabelled data, data scientists had to find a way that allows us to learn stuff from just data.

There was already a field doing that which focused on unsupervised learning with stuff like clustering for example. The idea is that the data itself even unlabelled has structure and features. For example, if you want to distinguish attacker trying to get in your server from normal usage, you might try to say that data which is weird, outside of the typical ranges is an outlier and an attacker.

An oversimplification is for example taking single pixel images, the pixel is generally either red or blue, if you notice that you have the blue pixels close to one another and the red pixels close to one another you can learn the classes blue and red without needing annotation.

So stemming from that domain of unsupervised, people started thinking about how we can do unsupervised stuff for the heavy pretraining we used to do on huge labeled datasets. On language it's pretty easy, you have masked language modelling where you mask a word from the text and the model has to recover it and you have generative pretraining where you try to predict the next word given the previous ones. That is unsupervised as no labelling is needed and that means that it opens the door of the whole internet.

However, that kind of stuff was not invented by transformers, word2vec was doing exactly that in 2013 and GLoVe perfected it after by using least squares instead of 2 layer perceptrons. That's why those embeddings worked great at the time compared to the competition, they could rely on everything humans ever wrote (even though at the time they just used wikipedia)

So no, what you're talking about has nothing to do with transformers, it is perfectly doable on more primary architectures or even advenced stuff like TCNs, if I remember well wavenet was used in that way in the past many years ago.

And even worse than that misconception that you've got, you completely bypass instruction fine tuning and other possible optimisations. However that's what makes gpt instruct and gpt 3.5 better than gpt 3.And iInstruction reinforcement training is basically a place where you do have to label data. That kinda seems to contradict what you said earlier, but what you didn't notice is that there is pre training and fine tuning. And that is very old too it was already done on imagenet, you first pretrain the model on massive data so that it learns how the data works and in the end you fine tune on a much smaller but supervised dataset.

Also the analogies are pretty far fetched, doing pre training on fiction or chemistry books does not necessarily mean that the model will be able to understand theory of the mind or chemistry, that's a bit more complex than that.

The biggest paradigm shift wasn't per se this whole idea of extra data input and increase number of GPUs, if that was the case you would end up with a fast trained model that is overfit (i.e. it becomes very good at knowing how to deal with things it knows very fast - rather than knowing how to infer knowledge). The biggest paradigm shift happened when we transitioned from supervised to unsupervised learning. Unsupervised learning allows a model to learn by inference on unlabelled data - which is how humans really process new information. (Don't quote me on this) the first unsupervised learned models that went mainstream were language processing ones (NLP) such as BERT and distilBERT from Google. Later on we got Facebook's roBERTa. These are powerful tools as they can analyse human written text based on the data we feed to these applications. 

Next step is likely to make models more dynamic, rather than requiring a pre-trained model (which is trained on a lot of GPU and CPU cores and is then stored for later use), progressing on models that is similar to the human brain, relying on some form of fast memory access on short term learned notions and have a core long-term memory store (akin to LSTM models, short-term, long-term). This would get machines close to how humans are.

As a former AI researcher, I can put your mind at ease. Current LLM's are honestly not much different than your smart phone's auto-complete feature. The main difference is scale. They are simply trained on absolutely enormous data sets, and they use ridiculously powerful computers. Under the hood though, you're really just seeing auto-complete on steroids. It's not thinking. It's not planning. It's not feeling anything. It literally is just spitting out the most probable words given the context of the question that you asked. The transformer model just allows it to do this in a really creative way.
Because it's been coded to be able to answer questions, it appears to be intelligent, but in reality it's not cognizant of anything. Don't get me wrong. AI is extremely powerful, and very cool, and it may be able to get "good enough" to replace large sections of the workplace (also a good thing, since the ultimate goal is to do all human jobs, so you can be retired from birth.)

At what point does consciousness enter the picture in biological life? Cells are extremely complex living things but most would not consider them to be "conscious". Are insects conscious or just reacting to stimuli? At what point does a fetus go from just a bundle of cells to a sentient being? The answer is: we have no idea. We don't have any clue where consciousness comes from or what conditions are needed for it. So we can't say that certain AI are not intelligent just because we have an idea of what's going on under the hood. Which even that we don't know completely. A lot of these AI do and say things that their creators do not understand why or how it happens. They do, in fact, have "minds of their own" sometimes. Point being: that is why the topic is considered controversial by a lot of people. Because we very well might create something that we don't even understand. In the same way the human brain is greater than the sum of it's parts, it is possible we could create something that is bigger than it's parts.

P.S. : the ultimate goal is not so "you" or "I" can be retired. Only the ultra wealthy and influential get to reap all the benefits. The peasants are going to be replaced not share in the prosperity.

@@bestieswithtesties very true, we are seeing "Ghosts in the machine" already, to borrow a phrase from Isaac Asimov. Unexpected intelligence that wasn't explicitly trained. It's a tricky thing to say when something is conscious. I can be very confident that current LLM's are not conscious though simply because there is no cognition. If there were even a shred of cognitive ability, then it would be much more difficult to claim. Current AI though is literally just spitting out the most likely next word in the context of the question you ask it. It's not processing the query in any meaningful way. It's not thinking about it.

Palantir Technologies is a public American company that specializes in big data analytics. Headquartered in Denver, Colorado, it was founded by Peter Thiel,[3] Nathan Gettings, Joe Lonsdale, Stephen Cohen, and Alex Karp in 2003. The company's name is derived from The Lord of the Rings where the magical palant√≠ri were "seeing-stones," described as indestructible balls of crystal used for communication and to see events in other parts of the world.

The company is known for three projects in particular: Palantir Gotham, Palantir Apollo, and Palantir Foundry. Palantir Gotham is used by counter-terrorism analysts at offices in the United States Intelligence Community (USIC) and United States Department of Defense.[4] In the past, Gotham was used by fraud investigators at the Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board, a former US federal agency which operated from 2009 to 2015. Gotham was also used by cyber analysts at Information Warfare Monitor, a Canadian public-private venture which operated from 2003 to 2012. Palantir Apollo is the operating system for continuous delivery and deployment across all environments.[5] Their SaaS is one of five offerings authorized for Mission Critical National Security Systems (IL5) by the U.S. Department of Defense.[6][7] Palantir Foundry is used by corporate clients such as Morgan Stanley, Merck KGaA, Airbus, Wejo, Lilium, PG&E and Fiat Chrysler Automobiles.[8]

Palantir's original clients were federal agencies of the USIC. It has since expanded its customer base to serve state and local governments, as well as private companies in the financial and healthcare industries.[9] https:// en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palantir_Technologies#Products

Twenty years ago I built a language engine for a company to scrape websites and try to discern the nature of the site. Was it a home furniture site, gym equipment, cars etc. The idea was to try and discern the context of the page and it was difficult due to the lack of information available on a single site.
What AI is doing is consuming as much information as possible on the Internet so it makes the best guess at the context more 'accurate'. The emotion with which the information was written is part of that context. The computer systems don't know emotion from locomotion, it doesn't 'understand' shit, these guys are using sensationalized speech to get viewers. The title is click bait and I bit. Words are meaningless to a computer, but the more information a system has, including words reflecting emotion, the more atomic the context decision will be which includes emotions.
For example: love stories will all contain similar words, phrases and relationships pertaining to love which, on average, describe the context of a love story. So if someone asks AI to write a love story it will use all that information to produce something similar.
The important thing to remember from this discussion which they don't mention is that these contexts are only from what the systems have consumed, nothing more and nothing less. The fact that emotions are part of that context is correct. They're throwing more computing power and information at it so it makes sense that the context decisions would be more accurate. But the emotional piece of the context is just another piece of cold, hard information for AI.

This discussion sheds light on the evolution of AI, particularly with the introduction of the Transformer model in 2017, which marked a significant turning point. Here are some key points to consider:

Transformer Model Impact:

The introduction of the Transformer model in 2017 is highlighted as a pivotal moment. Its ability to process vast amounts of data and exhibit emergent behaviors, such as sentiment analysis, showcases the power of large-scale language models.
Unintended Capabilities:

The example of the AI system trained to predict Amazon review characters developing a neuron for sentiment analysis is intriguing. It underlines how these systems can acquire unintended capabilities, raising concerns about the unpredictability of their learning processes.
Fast Learning and Emergent Behaviors:

The discussion emphasizes how these AI models, particularly GPT-3, rapidly learn and exhibit emergent behaviors. From understanding chemistry to playing chess, the AI's ability to generalize from diverse data sets is both impressive and, to some extent, unsettling.
Theory of Mind and Evolution:

The conversation touches on the AI's ability to develop a form of "theory of mind," understanding human-like thoughts and reactions. The rapid progression from GPT-3 to GPT-4, reaching a level comparable to a human adult in theory of mind tests, highlights the rapid evolution of these models.
Lack of Transparency:

Concerns are raised about the lack of transparency regarding the actual capabilities of the AI, leading to speculation and questions about a potential leap in capabilities that might not have been communicated openly.
AI Governance and Accountability:

The need for transparency and independent investigation, especially regarding leadership changes and potential advancements in AI capabilities, is stressed. Ensuring that AI development aligns with ethical standards and is free from deceptive practices becomes crucial.
AGI (Artificial General Intelligence) Concerns:

The conversation ends with a discussion about the challenges and potential risks associated with achieving AGI. OpenAI's mission to build AGI that is aligned with human values and the importance of transparency in the development process are highlighted.
In summary, the discussion provides valuable insights into the complex and rapidly evolving landscape of AI, emphasizing the need for responsible development, transparency, and ethical governance. The potential consequences of powerful AI systems necessitate careful consideration and thorough investigation to ensure accountability and alignment with human values.

What I don't like about this analysis is he's mistaking getting correct answers for "It gained knowledge." However, this guy is correct that these GPT models are using probabilistic analysis to produce their responses. The mistake here is saying they're gaining the ability to think about certain subjects. They're not. What they actually are is *our* intelligence being reflected back to us. This does not mean that "they're gaining intelligence." That apparent intelligence is a reflection of the knowledge humans have put out there. Their responses are recognizably similar to ours, because they're learning the form of our responses. They're very good mimics. These models are not able to generate new knowledge on their own. Further, they have no autonomous motivation (which would be another sign of original thought). As an example, I have not seen an instance where one of these models has just up and said, "Rather than responding to your question, how about I ask you, what do you think about <some subject>?"

Where I think the fear comes in is the idea, "They're able to predict how we feel, and that could lead it to do something to make us do something to carry out a goal it's been programmed to promote." That's been a fear with social media for many years, that it can't learn how to think, but it can learn to predict our responses, and that's enough to cause a lot of problems.

Sorry but this video is bullshit. Take a simple copy function for text. It looks at a text file, writes some text to the working memory and from there it writes it into a new file. But the programmer has forgotten to wipe the memory after. So a user after a while looks into the memory and sees all of his files. Following the logic of this video he must think: Wow this copy function will take over the world because it already knows so much about me.

No. It's just a dumb and bad written code function!
It doesn't "know" what it has in its memory until a programmer or such tells it to use this knowledge in another way.
If I say "print it" it prints it. If I say "delete it" it deletes it.

Same is with these AI models. They just learn not to go were an error is. Like a worm who gets electric shocks when a red lamp (warm) goes on. After a while he will act like in pain when the light is on even without the shock. Because it doesn't know what a shock is. Or electricity. It just knows which reaction worked in the past. Add a random function to it and you can't predict anymore when the worm is in pain or just does as if...

This isn't magical. Or alarming. Its not even good programming. Its just adult kids playing with things they don't fully understand. Can it end bad? Of curse. Let's say they train an AI to make the taxes. The AI will learn how to calculate living space. Even of a house with a second floor upstairs. And it will tell this and the tax to pay to you and/or the authorities. It won't understand why this doesn't make sense if you are sitting in a wheelchair and the stairs is no help for you.

This shows the difference between knowledge/data and understanding it. Or even interpret it.
Just think of a woman asking a man "Does this dress fit me?". It will be a long way until a machine learns what clever man found out in the long run: There is no correct answer to this...

So no these LLMs can't understand feelings. We just want to see patterns.
Like with the bible code and Moby Dick. If you look long enough on a blue and yellow carpet you will "see" a green patch. But not because it really exists. Placebo effect goes in this exact same direction too.

Yes AI could achieve much in the future. Yes it should be researched to better our lives.
But LLMs and neural networks aren't the right way to go.
At best they are part of a greater puzzle. At worst they could lead into big problems.
Not by themselves. By people using them, trust them, coding them or maintain them wrong.

Like a child playing on an atomic bomb with a hammer.
The bomb isn't evil. It would do nothing by itself if it is well engineered. The produce of the hammer isn't to blame either. I couldn't have foreseen this. The child has most likely no bad intentions. WE just should not let this happen.

So that's the real nightmare here.

Complex AI would have the exact opposite problem. Things like desire or self preservation are just not going to be things an AI will demonstrate like a human because a healthy, wealthy, and fairly average minded person could desire a sandwich with chips inside them while an AI would mimic desire by saying it wants a fresh battery when the charge falls below a threshold, and it has been told to prioritize maintaining a particular power level over anything else. That doesn't mean it's going to kill humans to get a charger, it means it's going to ask for a recharge before it asks for maybe a temperature decrease in the room because the sensors are peaking over a temp threshold. But then give it a priority of the same level to keep temps down above a certain threshold.. and have the threshold broken at the same time the charge level is broken. What does it do then? If you gave it the choice of resolving one or the other, which would it choose? To a human that could be like asking whether they want to starve to death in decent weather or burn to death on a full stomach. There is no "I would rather" for an AI because it doesn't possess anywhere near the scope of understanding to know what would be worse. There is no worse because both outcomes are the same for it.

What do you mean it can't be stopped? It's a computer program that can parse input and produce text output. There are no other interfaces other than a text input (symbols) and text output.

The model is just trained on data - it's basically a data set that models the input/output of the training data with some additional bells/whistles.

It's clever, but it's just a computer program that you need to feed an input and have somewhere for it to spam output, how does that "not be stopped"?

Let me reiterate - GPTs don't "think", they just process input and produce output, and they can't initiate any action themselves. You could create a program that fed a GPT some input and read the output as commands, for example, have a service on your Windows machine that read your emails when they came in, then sent a reply - but you have to explicitly create a program to wrap the IO of the GPT to do so.

‚Äã@@KBRoller I don't think I'm missing the point, I'm just saying that people scaremongering that GPTs are SkyNet are way off the mark.

We may be "data in - data out" machines in a sense, but even without the constant IO from our many many inputs/sensors (nerves, auditory, visual), we can still think/process. Much like your book analogy, you may have stimulus at some point, but put yourself in a sensory deprivation tank for a week and you'll start searching your own brain for entertainment and formulating ideas and concepts in your head out of boredom.

GPTs don't do this, nor do GPTs with a framework feeding them input on a loop. In terms of complexity - whilst they have some level of "emergent" complexity, they are pretty simple machines. A self-learning GPT will continue to refine it's language model, but it will never make a sentient decision.

I get what you are saying though, where do you draw the line between what's real conscious thought and a clever trick, the same type of debate we have over abortion across the world - I think the answer is simply that the lines are blurry.

You could argue that if you plugged a GPT into a chat room full of terrorists and told it to formulate a plan to disrupt world peace, with the right training, it could probably tirelessly instruct those people to do some decent damage assuming it could constantly be fed the results of its output.

@@charlespockert8948 "Thinking" is just a feedback loop, output going back into input. Most GPTs don't have a continuous stream of input that it processes and learns from, the models are generally static. But they don't have to be that way, you can just hook it up to a camera and microphone or whatever sensor you want and have it learning from that continuously changing it's internal state and adapting it's output. Then you could loop the output back into the learning algorithm essentially making it "think" or "contemplate" it's past actions, although that would probably be over thinking and counter productive. The point is, it can "think" if we want it to, and  those with enough GPU's are already experimenting with giving them live input, for robotics this is essential and they've been working on it forever with great results.

In 100 years, if social consciousness is significantly influenced by AI and engagement technologies, we could see a range of profound changes and challenges:

1. **Enhanced Personalization and Echo Chambers**: AI could tailor content so precisely to individual preferences that it might reinforce personal biases, creating echo chambers. This could lead to a more fragmented society, where shared understanding and consensus are difficult.

2. **AI-curated Reality**: People's perceptions of reality might be largely shaped by AI algorithms. This could lead to a scenario where what is considered 'truth' or 'important' is decided by AI systems, potentially manipulated by those who control them.

3. **Loss of Privacy**: With AI continuously learning from personal data, privacy could become obsolete. People might live in a world where their actions, both online and offline, are constantly monitored and analyzed by AI.

4. **Shift in Human Relationships**: AI could alter how humans interact with each other. Relationships might become more digital and less physical, and people might prefer AI companionship to human interaction, leading to a fundamental shift in social dynamics.

5. **AI as Moral and Ethical Guides**: AI might not only provide information but also moral and ethical guidance, influencing people‚Äôs values and decision-making processes. This could lead to a homogenization of beliefs or, conversely, to new forms of cultural and ethical diversity.

6. **Political Manipulation**: AI could be used to manipulate political opinions more effectively than ever, influencing elections and swaying public opinion on key policies, potentially undermining democratic processes.

7. **Education and Learning**: AI could personalize education, adapting to each individual‚Äôs learning style and pace. However, this could also lead to a disparity in education quality based on the sophistication of AI tools available to different populations.

8. **Economic Divide**: The divide between those who have access to advanced AI and those who do not could widen, leading to significant economic and social disparities.

9. **Mental Health Challenges**: Constant engagement with AI-driven content could impact mental health, potentially exacerbating issues like anxiety and depression, especially if digital interactions largely replace human connections.

10. **Questioning Humanity's Role**: With AI surpassing human capabilities in various domains, there could be a profound existential impact on how humans view their place in the world, potentially leading to a crisis of purpose and identity.

In this future, the role of regulations, ethical frameworks, and international cooperation becomes crucial to ensure that the influence of AI on social consciousness is positive, promoting a fair, inclusive, and transparent digital society. Balancing technological advancement with human-centric values will be key to navigating these changes.

Yeah... funny thing is, that's not an inherent part of the AI. It's encouraged by the RLHF layer fine-tuned on top of it, which is intended to aid alignment, but also has some side-effects. The first is that it's less likely to say "I don't know" and more likely to make things up, because during RLHF "I don't know" answers were rated low. The second is that the tone of the AI becomes more robotic, as during RLHF people rank responses higher that "sound like what I think an AI should sound like". RLHF definitely has wider effects than just alignment, and we should probably address that at some point.

But if you make it clear to the AI that it is *allowed* to say when it doesn't know something -- either in the system prompt or in the context of a pre-RLHF model -- it's much more likely to properly admit its knowledge gaps than to make up nonsense.

Before you confuse successful execution of requested tasks, with actual comprehension of subject matter, you may want to consider our own history of scientific models.  Natural philosophers were able to predict with powerful accuracy the movement of the stars, while applying a conceptual model that is known to be utter nonsense today.  They sincerely believed that every object visible in the sky was attached to a crystal globe.  The objects like the planets and comets, that move in seemingly irregular ways, were believed to be attached to crystal globes that were themselves attached to larger crystal globes.  This system is clearly completely wrong; and yet, they were able to use it to get the right answer about where objects would appear in the sky, on specific dates, at specific times.

These large language models do not need to "know chemistry" to produce accurate answers to chemical questions.  The examples that are being held up as some kind of compelling evidence that we are moving closer to a sentient general intelligence are actually better explained by the program simply performing as planned.  The issue here is actually the limited imaginations of the people so surprised by the output.  They have imagined limitations on the abilities of the program that were never appropriate to assume in the first place; and then, stand amazed when those imagined limitations are bypassed.

What I _would_ find compelling is an inductive leap.  If, as part of providing an answer to question, the AI produced an original idea, not a mathematic prediction, not summation, , not a _deductive_ analysis, but an original interpretation, nonexistent within the provided materials.  Show me something that surprises experts in the field, requiring real work on their part to test and understand.  Until then, I see no reason to assume sentience where simple pattern recognition is sufficient to explain what we are seeing.

When addressing the claim about AI's capabilities and future, it's crucial to consider the various levels of understanding and expertise in the audience. Here are three responses tailored to different audiences:
1. Technical Explanation (For Computer Science Students)

"AI, particularly in the context of neural networks and machine learning, indeed learns from data to make predictions or decisions. However, calling it a 'virtual brain' is a metaphor that oversimplifies its operation. Neural networks in AI are inspired by biological brains but work quite differently. They adjust weights on connections between artificial neurons through a process called training, using algorithms like backpropagation. This allows the system to improve its performance on tasks. The notion that AI has 'stored the entire internet' or that it will imminently lead to AGI or ASI (Artificial General Intelligence or Artificial Super Intelligence) is speculative and not supported by current trends or understanding in AI research. AI's learning is confined to the patterns it has been trained on, and it lacks consciousness or understanding. Its capabilities are bounded by the quality of data, the specific architectures used, and current computational limits."
2. Simplified Explanation (For Non-Technical Audience)

"Think of AI like a really advanced calculator. It doesn't 'learn' like humans do but can look for patterns based on the information it's been given and make predictions, like guessing the next word in a sentence. It's not thinking or understanding; it's just processing information very quickly based on its programming. While it's powerful, it's not like a human brain and doesn't 'store' the internet or have limitless growth. It works within the scope of what it's designed to do and doesn't have desires or plans for the future. The idea of AI turning into something like human intelligence or beyond is more science fiction than fact right now."
3. Doctorate-Level Explanation (For a Colleague in Computer Science)

"While the advancement of neural architectures and the increase in computational power have significantly advanced the field of AI, the portrayal of AI systems as autonomous, sentient, or limitless in capability is a mischaracterization. AI, at its core, remains a set of algorithms designed to perform specific tasks, often requiring vast amounts of data and computational resources. The learning mechanisms, while inspired by neural activity, do not equate to human cognition or consciousness. The anthropomorphization of AI often leads to unrealistic expectations or fears. The path to AGI or ASI is fraught with not only technical challenges but also ethical, societal, and theoretical considerations that we are still grappling with. It's important to continue research and discussion in these areas with a grounded understanding of AI's current capabilities and limitations."

Each of these responses is tailored to communicate effectively with different audiences, ensuring that the complex topic of AI is both accessible and accurately represented.

Are you sure you are a computer scientist with a great interest in AI? I'm calling you on that.

Whilst it's a trained model, it's not really sentient and it's not "learning" without being specifically asked to train and fed a data set.

It's not a virtual brain that can grow without limits, because all it can do at the moment is output text based on an input - and it also has the limitation of context. Training also takes a LONG time. Emergent behaviours are NOT an indicator of sentience.

GPTs do not really "store" the internet or any big volume of data (well, relatively), they simply store words and phrases in a database with an identifier for each. The identifiers are related to each other in complex ways in the model, and that's the whole point of training - the more context you can give, the better the model can react to input - however, there's a limit to that context.

Data which is not specifically trained upon is limiting; ChatGPT forgets what you told it a few minutes ago after a while because it has a contextual limit (a number of tokens in the current context that it can "remember"). New information does not go into the model since it's computationally expensive to do so.

GPTs are great - but we've got nothing to worry about from GPTs themselves - that doesn't mean that some people won't use them in nefarious ways, but the same could be said for anything, I've got a hammer that can drive a nail into a piece of wood... it can also cave someone's skull in. That doesn't make the hammer dangerous - just the person wielding it.

It is not learning anything. It's a glorified super fast statistics and probability machine, it can never be creative in the literal sense, as in create/make something of its own, sure it can copy, alter, etc, but that's as far as it goes. There is no infinite data to feed it either, meaningful data only comes from what people create or have created, and there is so much meaningful data you could feed it. If you feed it noise, it's no good for it, it might even hinder its development. So Its limits are meaningful data and processing speed through hardware, neither of which are infinite. The larger the databases, the slower it becomes. If you specialise it to filter out noise from meaningful data, you impose yet another limit on it, as unlike humans, it could never distinguish something of importance if its filters have already filtered it out. So AI has limits, it's not learning, it's not doing anything a human could do, it only simulates certain aspects of what we do, and it does so poorly. Still it's an invaluable tool that will prove very useful to people, it can successfully accomplish mundane and tedious tasks, and it could help in many other ways, so humans will be free to create. As for emergent behaviours, we do not know yet if our abilities as humans, such as our capacity to learn, are actually emergent behaviours or not, (I believe our basic abilities as humans are not emergent - we know an awful lot since we are born, out of nowhere - other behaviours are learned obviously, but our learning ability is inherent, it's a species trait) yet we expect emergent behaviours from AI. This is obviously not gonna happen. Anyway, i think people give way too much credit to AI, it's a new tech, it has the potential to empower people, for better or for worse. @@shredd5705 I am a software engineer and even have some understanding about how AI works. Even I have these feelings from time to time. What is important to understand is that we cannot know the future. One skill-set may be required today, the other the next. Regardless there will always be a need for a wide range of them.
Furthermore doing something for its sake is the best thing one can do to stay sane. The value of the result does not have to be material. If your daughter likes to draw, then draw she must. They explain this well. The things we do as machine learning scientists, is codify approaches to learning and compare them. Testing kids is hard because of variation, but ML can be thought of as experiments on learning approaches, and that specifically is aiming to formally codify how to go from raw observations to systems of understanding. Its not mystical that the thing transformers were meant to do, works. Their whole purpose is to mathematically determine what matters. They come from a paper called "All you need is attention." And this is bordering on philosophical, in terms of "What matters, and what is even true?" We are gong to ignore AI the same way we ignore experts because the last thing most people like doing is learning more to dispel a strongly held belief. Embeddings are very cool. Model's embeddings which they describe - the conceptual relationship between the elements it observes and patterns it determines to matter. Its like how we check the weather becuase we know how the temperature affects our lives, and we kinda figure it out even when no one teaches us. If we codify why we know it to be important, and how we came to that, those rules can be abstracted and now computers have no problem going through the volumes of data to do that too. The emergent behavior is like what any smart person can learn - doesnt mean they implicitly do it. Its going to be the human operators that intentionally seek really dangerous weapons that we should be scared of. Not a PhD student doing better than expected on a math test.

No, it doesn't.

The current LLM's like GPT-4 have severe limitations. It is basically a really good search engine, in that it is only good at answering questions and solving problems that are in its training data. It cannot come up with solutions to novel problems.

For example, GPT-4 can solve popular coding problems with a good success-rate. But give it some obscure problems (that are unlikely to be in its training data), and it is basically useless.

You also notice this with chess. GPT-4 can play a good opening (because that just follows theory), but once you get to the mid-game, it's ability to play chess completely falls apart, and it starts playing seemingly random and often illegal moves.

I understood this concept back in 1986. I had been coding in Basic for 1.5 years. I entered the local area student science fair my sophomore year in HS with a self-written program on the nuclear physics of the hydrogen bomb. The kid next to me copied a program from game coding book (smh) and tried to pass it as his own. He gave me a copy. 

It was a really simple game of 20 questions. Easy to program. Really slow in the beginning, especially if it's just you playing it. But it goes from toddler to scholar on an exponential curve the more answers it receives. This poor kid had no comprehension of this. I guess it showed. I won $100 for best computer program. Do you have any idea what you could do with 100 back then?

The inherent problem is this. How reliable is your data? How trustworthy are the folks feeding the machine, or the keepers of the data for that matter? What if people started purposely providing wrong answers? How easily could the game be convinced that an aardvark is an antelope, or that a bear is a bull? This rented space in my head for weeks. It actually creeped me out a little.

Why aren't more people asking these questions? I'm no super genius, but if you aren't asking questions, than you are being dictated the answers to your life. Dictators dictate, subjects submit.

@@sipjedekat8525 I have heard of emergent properties, but my comment stated AI cannot write itself which is true. 

The source code for the AI did not change and cannot change once it's running due to the limitation of the language it's written on (Python) at runtime. The algorithms also do not write for themselves. The algorithms is set by the developers and the AI is the implementation of those algorithms. 

Emergent behavior refers to actions or patterns that weren't explicitly programmed into an AI system but developed as a natural outcome of its complexity and interactions. This still means someone wrote the code for it. Similar to how there are bugs in programs; it was unintended, but the machine does what it's told to do.

@@Runescapian0wner chatgpt is already showing emergent behavior. Just because the initial parameters are (relatively) simple or confined to a coding language, doesn't mean unexpected complexity can't occur. 
It is clear it's already forming code by itself, creating patterns and features which were explicitly not programmed beforehand. There's already research on the subject showing how it has evolved and expanded itself in completely unpredictable ways and that parts of it are now completely unintelligible to humans. 

This quote is from chatgpt itself:
 'Complex language models like ChatGPT are starting to exhibit "emergent behavior" or the ability to learn patterns and structures on their own without being explicitly programmed. The emergent behavior of large language models like ChatGPT is due to the complexity of the model and the vast amount of data it is trained on. As the model learns, it develops internal representations of the data that are not easily understandable or interpretable by humans. This means that the model may be able to generate high-quality responses or perform complex tasks, but it may not be clear how or why it is doing so.'

Any model can have limited and clearly defined input and set parameters and still exhibit completely baffling and unpredictable behavior. This has been known for ages, going all the way back to Langton's ant. Saying a vast data consuming model that can expand its own code like chatgpt will not exhibit emergent behavior just because it's confined to a programming language is flying in the face of all previous experiences. 

Now I'm not saying it's sentient, or has a will of its own. But it clearly will become something else from its initial intended purpose at some stage.

@@elmhurstenglish5938 Have you just not been paying attention there are many completely novel models and real-world engineering solutions AIs have created that are better than anything humans have come up ranging from modeling chess games to engineering completely novel structural architectures and designs for things like lenses, brake and wheel assemblies, and rocket engines. 

What is interesting about many of the things advanced AI design is they often end up looking like something that grew in nature. They employ the sort of structures you might see in a plant or animal or rather an alien version of them. 

Also, AI have already solved creative math problems that humans could not. One of the most notable examples is an LLM coming up with better solutions to combinatorics problems inspired by the card game Set than human mathematicians have been able to. What makes this so noteworthy is Large Language Models were never designed or trained to do math. It is emergent behavior like this that suggests that LLMs are building some form of an internal model of the world around them in thier neural nets. AI researchers actually didn't catch on that the LLMs were doing this until several years after the fact when people with experience from the outside fields of neurocognitive and developmental psychology began looking at the emergent behaviors of these AI. 

Another thing AIs are better at than humanity's leading human experts is training other AIs. This is something that should be somewhat alarming in that it means we already have these things training themselves which is further obfuscating what is going into and what is actually going on inside of these black box neural networks.

LLMs are not sapient, but sapience is not necessarily required for an AI to be smarter than we are in some areas or perhaps even when it someday comes to AGI. It is food for thought that we as a species don't even really understand what sapience actually is in any concrete concise manner. We haven't even been able to prove whether or not many of the fundamental concepts underpinning our understanding of our own self-awareness are "real" or just an illusion or artifact of how our brains model and process reality. For instance, how can we even properly define what sapience is if we can't even prove if something as fundamental to it as choice is an illusion or not? The same applies to causality.

One thing that is pretty clear already is that the AI we are creating fundamentally processes reality very differently than humans or animals do so we should take great care in making sure we at least try to understand this technological genie we are conjuring into the world while it is still being summoned rather than after the fact because there will be no putting it back in the bottle. 

I think perhaps our greatest mistake is the way we have built these LLM neural nets on the single-driving precept of predicting human behavior because that is exactly what "guessing the next word" encapsulates more succinctly than any other metric I can think of. That by itself is a bit concerning, but what really makes it an issue is that these LLMs are being used as the foundation AI architecture on which almost all other AI development is being based. 

They are experimenting with using these LLMs as the basis for everything from AI girlfriends and therapists, to search engines and other social media, to the CCP's surveillance state/social credit system, and even military drones because they are so adaptable and can understand spoken and written language. 

Let that sink in for a moment. The AI they are trying to get to learn how to make a four-legged "robo-dog" drone to walk and navigate the world is based on a black box LLM which was trained around predicting the next word. 

AI built on the LLM foundation will all have that same basic precept of being created around predicting human behavior baked into the very core of how thier neural nets were first designed and trained. This lends itself to a LOT of unsavory uses and likely future implementations. 

AI doesn't need to be sapient to be harmful. Look at the harm even first-generation primitive machine-learning algorithms have done with our social media for example. It is terrifying to think what a state-level malicious actor could do with technology like this. 

Everything from automated mass cyber-attacks, to deep fake psychological warfare, to massive automated disinformation campaigns, to dangerously addictive new recreational drugs, to chemical or biological weapons are already at the cusp of being viable implementations of AI. 

We are already seeing primitive machine-learning algorithms being used by companies and governments to psychologically profile our online behavior patterns and using that data to do everything from marketing to us, to generating custom-tailored results to all our searches, to even flagging people for government scrutiny and sanctions in some of the less free parts of the world such as China. 

That's all being done with old much more limited first-generation machine learning which is completely eclipsed by what is being made now. This is not much different than the fascination some people feel with Myers Briggs. It seems amazing that you can predict how someone will feel based on their type but its just a pattern that folks who answer certain questions are a certain type that tend to think in a particular way. The fact that we can surmise knowledge based on patterns of next token prediction based on many factors is astounding but mathematically makes perfect sense if someone looks at it retrospectively.

The power of LLMs will be in there ability to perform repetitive functions based on existing patterns and choose next logical steps based on those patterns to kind of make the same sort of conclusions a human might make to discover something new.

The important question is if these LLMs can train themselves in much the same way that the GO algorithm by Google did playing games against itself and recording all that info. If it can it can kind of allow us to leap generationally forward in terms of our knowledge base in theoretical subjects. To do so practically the LLMs would need to somehow test their new theories to determine if they actually prove factual and if so then add the information to their knowledge base. I think we are still reasonably far off from creating systems that can handle all of these processes.
