Sorry.. but this NOT true. I know, I've worked with AI extensively. And I know HOW it works . It works by taking all the data on the internet or any other information you give it, then in statistically WEIGHTS what is COMMONLY used. Then, when you give it a prompt, it regurgitates this statistically-weighted information using something called a markov chain. A markov chain is a tool AI uses to regurgitate this information. And AI sounds really smart. But it isn't. AI understands and knows absolutely NOTHING. Its "learning" is simply more and better regurgitation. It can't know what you think or what you feel. It can't create a new idea or innovation. It can't do anything other than regurgitate using its programming. Like any home computer or software program, AI uses good old-fashioned binary code. Binary code is simply on and off messages in computer language that does things we all know, like word processing and calculations. This is NOT intelligence. AI is simply more advanced computing. The human brain is actually 2 practically separate brains (left and right). The left acts as the emissary and the right as the master. While what they are saying is not nessecarily wrong, it is not quite true either. These models got extremely good at predicting characters/tokens, but lacked the actual understanding of the topic, such as chemistry, maths, physics, chess and so on, it just learned how to recreate text, based on tons of data. However when probed deeply, it became quite obvious it had no real understanding of the topic at hand. Transformers allow for the systems to become exponentially bigger just by throwing more data and compute at them, but the systems still just have internal statistical representeations of language, while the "knowledge" of the topic is tightly bound to the representation of language.
But currently there are tons of new models emerging, which are so called "expert systems" and those seem to actually be able to build the understanding (to some extent), that the previous models lacked, by having mutliple systems working together, with the "main agent" being a GPT 3.5/4-like LLM with really good language processing capabilities coupled with systems trained on specific topics, posing as the expert. Those are the systems which seem to actually have the capabilities talked about in the video.

This is all BS. The AI doesn't "learn" anything. It just loads a lot of content into its database and paraphrases the stuff back to you in response to questions.  Its just a new search response that sounds more human. Its a parlor trick.. much the same as what a fortune teller does.

It's not that hard to read a lot of background information and take the next logical step.   Thats not powerful, its just fast.. which is useful. But its not an indicator of intelligence.

Unlike machibes, humans .. especially really smart humans are able to figure things out with very _little_ background information. Real genius is the ability to synthesize new knowledge. AI _cannot_ do that. All it "knows" is the data u feed it. Give it 20 years of Fox news... and it will sound like a conservative pundit. Feed it CNN.. it will sound liberal.  Feed it the writings of Tolstoy, it will paraphrase your answer as a existential dilemma.  Give it the works of Jordan Peterson and it will psychoanalyze your response.

Human IQ does not increase proportionately with  the amount of reading and learning .. it remains the same.  AI accuracy .. and inaccuracy depends directly on the data loaded unto a model.  As such, the real fear is in becoming over-reliant on AI.. and then retrieving back wrong or biased content.

@@LarryBonsonAs a software developer: there is often a lot of trial and error in programming. You write the code you think will work, then it doesn't, then you spend ungodly amounts of time debugging and trying to understand why it doesn't work, then you fix the bits you find, then it still doesn't work, rinse and repeat until it works. If something works without much debugging, that's a surprise. If it then *exceeds* your expectations of its capabilities, then you're *aghast.*

@@Runescapian0wner That's.... not true. The designers of the AI -- that is, the engineers implementing the Transformer architecture -- designed a system to predict the next set of characters in a piece of text. A fancy autocomplete, basically. And... that's all. They did *not* tell it how to do *literally anything else* and had no idea it would be able to do much more than complete text. The thing about machine learning is that it explicitly does *not* just "do what it's programmed to do". The programmers write an algorithm for *how to learn things,* and then the AI learns all on its own from there.

In fact, once the AI has learned stuff, we don't even know how it understands anything. The weights it learns in its network are a mostly meaningless black box to humans; that's why interpretability is a huge field of AI research, trying to probe at the trained model weights to figure out what the hell they represent. Think of it like a brain: even if you could see the connections between every single neuron, you still wouldn't know how that translates to knowledge, sensations, understanding, perceptions, memories, skills, etc. You'd have to probe the connections and see what behavior occurs, then reverse-engineer that to try and figure out what the connections mean. That's what interpretability studies do; because we *don't* tell the AI how to do anything other than "how to learn".
